title.narrative: EDUCATION DRR/RESILIENCE

description.narrative: The education system at all levels has increased capacity to build resilience and prepare children and school communities to respond to emergencies and disasters particularly in target countries., which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Access To Quality Learning Opportunities (Covid), Equitable Access To Quality Education, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more pre-primary, primary and lower secondary school aged and school-aged children particularly the most vulnerable, are in school and learning.

title.narrative: The education system at all levels has increased capacity to build resilience and prepare children and school communities torespond to emergencies and disasters particularly in target countries.

description.narrative: Pacific countries continued implementation of COVID-19 education response plans, both for immediate response and long-term system strengthening to ensure learning continuity, safe school operations, and the physical, social and emotional well-being of all students, whether schools are open or closed. In addition, countries worked to integrate pandemic preparedness within existing education in an emergency (EiE) and disaster risk reduction (DRR) systems and to strengthen contingency planning for COVID-19 and other emergencies. Fiji, the only country with an extended school closure in 2021, initiated a phased reopening of schools in November 2021. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:03/02/2022
